and with what effects? In doing so, it highlights the ambivalent place of the sacred in the self-image of modern states and jurisprudence. For if it is the case that, particularly in the developed West, contemporary law posits a fundamental conceptual divide between sacred and secular, it nevertheless remains true that the assertion of that divide has its own history, one that defines Western modernity itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh1 aConnolly, William E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDouglas, Lawrence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDouglas, Lawrence, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFitzpatrick, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKatz, Marion Holmes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevinson, Sanford, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSarat, Austin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSarat, Austin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aStolzenberg, Nomi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aUmphrey, Martha Merrill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aUmphrey, Martha Merrill, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150362639340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503626393423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503626393/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles